# Cursor Rules for mpct Swift Project

## Project Overview
This is a Swift CLI project targeting macOS 15+ with modular architecture including different modules that aim to help engineers with scripts boilerplate locally and on the CI.

## Language & Platform
- Swift 6.1 with strict concurrency enabled
- macOS 15+ target
- Use modern Swift language features and syntax

## Code Style & Formatting
- Use .editorconfig and follow swift-format configuration in .swift-format for editor consistency
- Use 2-space indentation (never tabs)
- Line length limit: 120 characters
- Use triple-slash comments (///) for documentation
- Prefer single-line property getters when possible
- Use early exits sparingly **guard** (follow existing patterns)
- No semicolons except where required
- No force unwrapping in production code (use sparingly in tests)

## Architecture & Design Patterns
- Follow the existing modular structure: ENV, CI, Logs, mpct
- Use dependency injection where appropriate
- Prefer composition over inheritance
- Keep modules loosely coupled
- Use protocols for abstraction (like CIInterface)

## Concurrency & Threading
- All types must be Sendable where appropriate
- Use async/await for asynchronous operations
- Prefer structured concurrency over callbacks
- Use actors for mutable shared state
- Follow strict concurrency guidelines

## Error Handling
- Use Result types for operations that can fail
- Prefer throwing functions for recoverable errors
- Use proper error types, not generic Error
- Handle errors gracefully in CLI context

## Testing
- Use the new Testing framework
- Write unit tests for all modules
- Test both success and failure scenarios
- Mock external dependencies where needed
- Follow existing test structure in Tests/ directory
- Add **GIVEN**/**WHEN**/**THEN** comments. Add short comments on what's heppening in each GIVEN/WHEN/THEN block.
- Name the system under test as **sut**.
- Group tests in **@Suite**.
- Use mixed case when naming test methods **test_function/property_testExplanation**.
- For @Test use the following **@Test("#function/property test explanation")**.
- For unit tests stick to testing outputs not the behaviour.

## Dependencies
- Use ArgumentParser for CLI argument parsing
- Use Swift Log for logging (via Logs module)
- Use Yams for YAML parsing
- Use Swift Crypto for cryptographic operations
- Keep external dependencies minimal and justified

## Documentation
- Document all public APIs with triple-slash comments
- Include parameter and return value descriptions
- Use proper Swift documentation formatting
- Keep documentation concise but comprehensive

## File Organization
- One main type per file
- Group related functionality in extensions
- Use file-scoped private access level where appropriate
- Follow existing directory structure
- Keep main.swift minimal (entry point only)

## Environment Variables
- Use ENV module for all environment variable access
- Use dynamic member lookup for clean syntax
- Handle missing environment variables gracefully

## Performance
- Prefer value types over reference types
- Use lazy evaluation for expensive computations
- Minimize allocations in hot paths
- Profile performance-critical code

## Security
- Validate all external inputs
- Use secure defaults
- Don't log sensitive information
- Use Swift Crypto for cryptographic operations

## Code Quality
- Prefer explicit over implicit
- Use descriptive variable and function names
- Keep functions small and focused
- Avoid deep nesting. If needed use 3 levels maximum
- Use guard statements for early validation

## Swift-Specific Best Practices
- Use optionals correctly and safely
- Prefer let over var
- Use property wrappers where appropriate
- Leverage Swift's type system for safety
- Use enums with associated values for complex states
- Follow naming conventions (camelCase for variables, PascalCase for types)

## Package Management
- Keep Package.swift up to date
- Use semantic versioning for dependencies
- Prefer official Apple packages when available
- Document dependency choices in comments

## Build & Development
- Use mise.toml for tool version management
- Support swift-format for code formatting
- Maintain clean build warnings

## CLI Best Practices
- Provide helpful error messages
- Support --help for all commands
- Use proper exit codes
- Handle interruption gracefully
- Provide verbose/quiet modes where appropriate

## Anti-Patterns to Avoid
- Don't use force unwrapping in production code
- Don't use implicitly unwrapped optionals unnecessarily
- Don't use singletons unless absolutely necessary
- Don't hardcode strings that should be configurable
- Don't mix synchronous and asynchronous code patterns
- Don't use global state
- Don't ignore compiler warnings

## Review Checklist
Before submitting code:
- [ ] All tests pass
- [ ] Code follows formatting rules. Use `mise tasks run format` command to format code
- [ ] Documentation is complete
- [ ] Error handling is appropriate
- [ ] Concurrency safety is maintained
- [ ] Performance implications considered
- [ ] Security best practices followed
